  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3339076464" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3339076464" />
    <a title="Algernon (Darth Anyan)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4728718-algernon-darth-anyan"><img alt="Algernon (Darth Anyan)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1553101944p2/4728718.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3339076464?book_show_action=true">Jun 02, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Algernon (Darth Anyan)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Algernon (Darth Anyan)" href="/user/show/4728718-algernon-darth-anyan">Algernon (Darth Anyan)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4728718-algernon-darth-anyan?shelf=2020">2020</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3339076464" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10571770201440786816"><br/><b> What I do best are the absurdities of daily life: I observe, add up these observations, increase them to the nth degree and draw the square root from them, but with a different factor from the one I increased them by. </b><br/> <br/>Hans Schnier is not asking much from life: to be allowed to love Marie, to marry her, to have children and to grow old together. To be able to express himself through his pantomime art, inspiring and entertaining his audience. He hopes for respect from his parents, quality time w</span>
  <span id="freeText10571770201440786816" style="display:none"><br><b> What I do best are the absurdities of daily life: I observe, add up these observations, increase them to the nth degree and draw the square root from them, but with a different factor from the one I increased them by. </b><br> <br>Hans Schnier is not asking much from life: to be allowed to love Marie, to marry her, to have children and to grow old together. To be able to express himself through his pantomime art, inspiring and entertaining his audience. He hopes for respect from his parents, quality time with his brother and sister, stimulating friends and good conversations. He’s 28 years old, a bitter drunk without a dime in his pockets and contemplating suicide. Because everything of value has been taken away from him, and Hans is an outcast.<br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1591128548i/29584428.jpg" alt="hans" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>His rich parents repudiated Hans after he seduced Marie and trained to be a clown. His sister was killed absurdly and unnecessarily in the last days of the Third Reich. His brother has joined a Catholic seminary and wants to become a priest. His Protestant father believes giving money to his son is a sin. His beloved Marie has left him to go back to the Catholic church because he would not sign away the future of their presumptive children. His last cringeworthy gig ended in a knee injury and a call to retire from his agent.<br><br><b> Now my injured knee was a good excuse for lying on the sofa, smoking cigarettes, and inhaling self-pity. </b><br><br>Hans Schnier retreats to his former apartment in Bonn with a bottle of brandy and a telephone book, revisiting the past to map out his abrupt descent into depression, rage calling all relatives and acquaintances to either lend him a few marks or to help him get Marie back. At the first couple of chapters I had very little sympathy for Hans, crying into his bottle and wallowing in what I perceived as self-inflicted misery. Even his artistic intransigence I found pretentious and self-centered. Why couldn’t the young mr. Schnier learn to compromise and adapt like the rest of us?<br><br><b> There’s nothing more depressing for people than a clown they feel sorry for. It’s like a waiter coming up in a wheelchair to bring you your beer. </b><br><br>I was very close to give up on the novel because of this intense initial dislike of Hans Schnier defeatist and selfish narration <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ and I include here the almost rape of Marie in the scene of seduction  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, but the longer I listened to this novel-long monologue, the more convinced I became that Heinrich Boll deserves the Nobel prize and the general critical acclaim he received.<br>Hans Schnier is more than a simple clown. He is an artist out of a burning need to understand the world, find an expression for all the diverse emotions and aspirations of his generation and, maybe, be a factor of change for the better. His choices of material for the pantomimes, such as they are described in the novel, are not meant for commercial success but as a catalyst for exposing the rot that underlies bourgeois complacence. Like Lenny Bruce at about the same period in time, Hans Schnier sees the role of comedian as that of an agent provocateur, as the voice of our collective conscience crying out against the rise of the hypocrites. <br><br>Hans deploys his sarcastic wit in vain over the telephone calls as the recipients don their armor of self-righteousness, fake piety and hollow intellectual discourse. The humour becomes indistinguishable from pure rage, as Hans is ready to <i> ... punch Kalick in the nose, call Sommerwild a popish hypocrite and accuse the other members of the executive committee of German Catholicism of inciting to lechery and adultery. </i><br><br>Without trying to be exhaustive, Kalick is a former schoolmate of Hans who snitched on his friends as Jews or unpatriotic to the Nazis, gave speaches at the Hitler Youth meetings and now acts as a pillar of the national reconciliation. Sommerwild is the leader of a Catholic group that organizes political and scriptural debates and also worked behind Hans’ back to convince Marie to leave him because he is not pious enough. Schnitzler is a mediocre author who used to hang around the Schnier mansion, exhorting others to be patriotic while he scrounged for scraps from the patrons purses. Hans holds him responsible for the death of his sister Henrietta, who was sent to an anti-aircraft volunteer unit only days before the Americans occupied Bonn.<br><br><i> And yet he was the one who forced my mother to make us join up, me in the Hitler Youth and Henrietta in the BDM. “In this hour, dear lady, we simply all have to pull together, stand together, suffer together.” </i><br><br>The Schnitzlers of the world are alive and well today, many of them in positions of absolute political power that they abuse in a similar manner when it comes to global pandemics or civil unrest.<br><br>These are only a couple of examples from the numerous instances of hypocrisy that changed my impression of Hans Schnier from a selfish punk to an almost textbook definition of a martyr. Indeed, time after time in his telephone calls with diverse politicians, clerics, bankers, tour agents, family or friends, Hans the atheist comes across as better acquainted with the spirit of Christianity, that core kernel of compassion, than his seminary educated, socially successful but dry hearted contemporaries.<br><br><b> For the outsider – and everyone in this world is an outsider in relation to everyone else – something always seems worse or better than it does for the one directly concerned, whether that something is good luck or bad luck, an unhappy love affair or an “artistic decline.” </b><br><br>Even regarding the relationship with Marie was thrown in a new light as I learned to see in Hans not the aggressive seducer, but the victim of an outdated yet strict moral code that puts more value in dogma than in sincere devotion. I still found the downbeat tone of the book hard to take in more than small doses of about a chapter a day, but by the end of the story I really hoped that Hans would find some reprieve from his trials and tribulation, some honest and true friend in the city that could share his pain and relieve his loneliness.<br>As it happened with other very sad stories about dreamers and loners who find it hard to adapt to a sick world (“Stoner”, “Ebenezer Le Page”) my final rating is an expression not of great entertainment, because ultimately true art is not supposed to be escapist popcorn, but of a provocative and unsettling challenge to the status quo.<br><br><b> “What kind of man are you?” he asked.<br>“I am a clown,” I said, “and I collect moments. Goodbye.” I hung up. </b><br><br>&gt;&gt;&gt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&lt;&lt;&lt;<br><br>two notes from the afterword:<br><br><i> So close was Boll’s family to the edge of survival in those years that when he received 1000 marks in prize money from Gruppe 47 in 1951, he immediately sent it to his wife and children so they could buy something to eat. </i><br><br>[So that is the reason the details about Hans Schnier’s poverty are so poignant and the question of artistic integrity such a central theme of the novel.]<br><br><i> While Boll worked on ‘The Clown’ he was also translating ‘Catcher in the Rye’ into German. </i><br><br>[the whole review could be written as a parallel between Holden Caulfield and Hans Schnier, but not by me since it’s been decades since I read Salinger]<br><br></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></["br"]></span>
  <a data-text-id="10571770201440786816" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


