<div id="review_3351995945" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3351995945" />
    <a title="Greta" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/111566858-greta"><img alt="Greta" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1586844759p2/111566858.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3351995945?book_show_action=true">May 23, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Greta" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Greta" href="/user/show/111566858-greta">Greta</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/111566858-greta?shelf=classics">classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3351995945" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16130961239452457729">Germany in 1950 as nationalistic as in 1930?<br/><br/>The clown is a novel by Nobel price winner Heinrich Böll and tells about a man who looses the marriage to his wife and the connection to himself in the post war time of the 50s and 60s in the former nationalistic Germany.<br/><br/>The protagonist Mr. Schnier turns his back to the traditions of his family, which just starts to benefit of the economic bursts after the war and has history of participating in the nationalistic regime. Instead of turning to politics </span>
  <span id="freeText16130961239452457729" style="display:none">Germany in 1950 as nationalistic as in 1930?<br /><br />The clown is a novel by Nobel price winner Heinrich Böll and tells about a man who looses the marriage to his wife and the connection to himself in the post war time of the 50s and 60s in the former nationalistic Germany.<br /><br />The protagonist Mr. Schnier turns his back to the traditions of his family, which just starts to benefit of the economic bursts after the war and has history of participating in the nationalistic regime. Instead of turning to politics or economics and the Catholic Church, as expected from him he decides to become a comedian/clown and stays an atheist. Still he marries the catholic Marie Derkum, but their marriage breaks due to their different religious believes and Schnier falls into depression and alcoholism, entering a downward spiral. <br /><br />Special about this book is that it only captures a few hours, starting with his arrival in Bonn.<br /><br />He starts to call family members and friends looking for hold, but can’t find support. His parents were strong believer of the nationalism and his mother works in an anti racism committee that contradicts her beliefs, while his father is a successful entrepreneur. He talks about his teachers who still thought them nationalistic ideas and grieves over his sister who died during the war, because his mother send her to fulfill her duty.<br /><br />The main point of this novel is the criticism of the non reflective society changes after the Second World War. The clearance of nationalistic believes wasn’t successful and people with nationalistic believes were all over the place, in official positions in the educational system and in the economic sector. The BRD and the Catholic Church didn’t manage to work through the nationalistic past, which systems require unquestionable following of their pendants.<br /><br />What I don’t like about the book is that it’s very constructed. Also I don’t really understand why the protagonist had to become a clown of all reasons. It creates the strongest contrast possible for sure but I feel like it also undermines the message.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16130961239452457729" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

