    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1356649081" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1356649081" />
    <a title="João Fernandes" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28882833-jo-o-fernandes"><img alt="João Fernandes" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1428006997p2/28882833.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1356649081?book_show_action=true">Aug 06, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="João Fernandes" class="user" itemprop="url" name="João Fernandes" href="/user/show/28882833-jo-o-fernandes">João Fernandes</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781935554172" href="/book/show/8971686-the-clown">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/28882833-jo-o-fernandes?shelf=nobel">nobel</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/28882833-jo-o-fernandes?shelf=war">war</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1356649081" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5428636024828145953">Heinrich Böll, winner of the 1972 Nobel Prize in Literature, once said that the only topics that were interesting for him to write were love and religion. <br/><br/><i>The Clown</i> follows Hans Schnier, a depressed, fallen out of grace, broke clown, as he makes a series of phone calls to his acquaintances and relatives in an attempt to get some money and learn about his ex-girl friend, Marie. Marie, a Catholic, left Hans not only because of their ideological differences but because her religious beliefs made he</span>
  <span id="freeText5428636024828145953" style="display:none">Heinrich Böll, winner of the 1972 Nobel Prize in Literature, once said that the only topics that were interesting for him to write were love and religion. <br /><br /><i>The Clown</i> follows Hans Schnier, a depressed, fallen out of grace, broke clown, as he makes a series of phone calls to his acquaintances and relatives in an attempt to get some money and learn about his ex-girl friend, Marie. Marie, a Catholic, left Hans not only because of their ideological differences but because her religious beliefs made her feel guilty because they were "living in sin", and goes off to marry a proper Catholic.<br /><br />Hans, born into a wealthy family, to an estranged father and a maniac mother - a woman who has every claim to the title of 'biggest hypocrite' - is our window into German society and to the Catholic mindset. Through his memories and conversations, we see the hypocrisy that followed the collapse of Nazi Germany, as exemplified by his mother, who went from "fashionably Nazi sympathiser against the Jewish Yankees" to "President of the Executive Committee for the Reconciliation of Racial Differences". <br /><br />In Hans' relationship with Marie and his subsequent obsession and hatred of Catholicism we also see their inability to take responsibility for their own mistakes and differences, which in a way is exactly the type of apologetic denial he sees and hates in Catholics and former Nazi supporters - making Hans sort of a hypocrite, too.<br /><br /><i>The Clown</i> provides an informed look into German society under Hitler and the post-war denial of responsibility by some supporters of the Nazi cause, as well as the effects of religious differences on interpersonal relationships. <br /><br />It's a book that is incredibly witty and at the same time utterly depressing, which is no small feat. I'd highly recommend it and am looking forward to reading more of Böll's work.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="5428636024828145953" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

