<div id="review_73481569" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/73481569" />
    <a title="Julia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2719191-julia"><img alt="Julia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1252501222p2/2719191.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/73481569?book_show_action=true">Oct 04, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Julia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Julia" href="/user/show/2719191-julia">Julia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9783423004008" href="/book/show/1931990.Ansichten_eines_Clowns">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2719191-julia?shelf=german-lit">german-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer73481569" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13190302821921029603">I always had a dislike against clowns, maybe that&apos;s why i&apos;d been avoiding this book for such a long time until my brother recommended it to me really enthusiastically, and i was surprised to find the main character one of the most moving i&apos;ve recently encountered. Heinrich Schnier is the typical outcast, a melancholic clown who&apos;s got the terrible gift to see throuth people&apos;s falseness and pompous self-righteousness....at the beginning i was a little bit surprised to find catholics the main targe</span>
  <span id="freeText13190302821921029603" style="display:none">I always had a dislike against clowns, maybe that's why i'd been avoiding this book for such a long time until my brother recommended it to me really enthusiastically, and i was surprised to find the main character one of the most moving i've recently encountered. Heinrich Schnier is the typical outcast, a melancholic clown who's got the terrible gift to see throuth people's falseness and pompous self-righteousness....at the beginning i was a little bit surprised to find catholics the main target of his musings, but apparently the topic was way more important in the time written (beginning of the sixties in post-war Germany...). even though society has greatly changed since then and Heinrich Schnier would probably criticize other parts of society, the hipocrisy he feels everywhere would still be there. <br />it's heart-breaking how Schnier describes his loss of Marie, the catholic woman who runs away from him because she can't stand the sinful state of not being married to him - while Schnier seems so much more moral than most of the catholics Marie has contact with and admires. Not caring about those things himself, he always wakes her for mass on sundays, pays the taxi when she's late - he thinks he really SEES the woman he loves, and he loves her in exactly the understanding and supporting way every woman should be loved - still, Marie has got different ideas and attitudes which finally lead her away from him...<br /><br /><br />i found Heinrich's relationships with his family even more interesting than the one with Marie - all the characters are just perfectly well-rounded, they're complex personalities and it's hard to form a judgment on them, despite of their obious weaknesses. Böll is a master of depicting people with just a couple of words, and his prose is fantastically simple - i wholeheartedly recommend this book to anyone, and hope that the translations are up to the masterful writing of the original....<br />memorable scenes and characters, real masterpiece!<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13190302821921029603" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


