<div id="review_1494614794" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1494614794" />
    <a title="Martin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3293999-martin"><img alt="Martin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1610732062p2/3293999.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1494614794?book_show_action=true">Jan 04, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Martin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Martin" href="/user/show/3293999-martin">Martin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3293999-martin?shelf=classics-all-time-children-modern">classics-all-time-children-modern</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1494614794" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6834041685216987889">This was really, really good. One of the saddest books I’ve ever read, a truly melancholic novel, filled with strange humor that makes you laugh and cry at the same time. <br/><br/>Heinrich Böll takes the popular trope of the sad clown and uses it to tell a captivating story about a lonely man, longing for the girlfriend who left him. It’s a story about the hypocrisy of the world we live in – religious, social, moral and all other kinds of hypocrisy. It’s set in a post-World War II times, and the main cha</span>
  <span id="freeText6834041685216987889" style="display:none">This was really, really good. One of the saddest books I’ve ever read, a truly melancholic novel, filled with strange humor that makes you laugh and cry at the same time. <br /><br />Heinrich Böll takes the popular trope of the sad clown and uses it to tell a captivating story about a lonely man, longing for the girlfriend who left him. It’s a story about the hypocrisy of the world we live in – religious, social, moral and all other kinds of hypocrisy. It’s set in a post-World War II times, and the main character observes as the most faithful servants of Hitler are now repentant Catholics, faithfully serving God. The novel is incredibly anti-religious and explores the differences between human morality and catholic ethics. <br /><br />And in the heart of all that is a story about one man’s inability to move on, to accept that he has lost the love of his life. And the reason for that inability lies in the fact that he didn’t lose his loved one – she was taken from him, persuaded to leave him with arguments that may make some sense from a religious perspective, but make absolutely no sense from human perspective. All in all, this novel is sad cry for humanity and love in a world of hypocrisy. <br /><br />And I loved every word of it. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6834041685216987889" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


