<div id="review_25783475" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/25783475" />
    <a title="Michele" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/46008-michele"><img alt="Michele" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1565477541p2/46008.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/25783475?book_show_action=true">Jun 28, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michele" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michele" href="/user/show/46008-michele">Michele</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780380003334" href="/book/show/3045710-the-clown">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer25783475" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18358460370114327223">I rescued an ancient paperback version from our basement during a recent flood. My husband (the philosophy major) had picked it up for &quot;fun&quot; reading sometime after college as he was exploring what he called &quot;existentialist&quot; writing. I guess it could be considered Camus or Sartre territory, but my immediate impression of the hero-antihero was of a slightly older version of Holden Caulfield from J.D. Salinger&apos;s &quot;The Catcher in the Rye.&quot; <br/><br/>&quot;The Clown&quot; is a 20-something frustrated performer in post-WW</span>
  <span id="freeText18358460370114327223" style="display:none">I rescued an ancient paperback version from our basement during a recent flood. My husband (the philosophy major) had picked it up for "fun" reading sometime after college as he was exploring what he called "existentialist" writing. I guess it could be considered Camus or Sartre territory, but my immediate impression of the hero-antihero was of a slightly older version of Holden Caulfield from J.D. Salinger's "The Catcher in the Rye." <br /><br />"The Clown" is a 20-something frustrated performer in post-WWII Germany whose longtime lover has left him for a more traditional married life with a devout Catholic. His wealthy family is implicated in his angst and his anger against the Nazis, the Catholics, and the new world order. Like Salinger's hero, he defines and redefines morality in a perverse world. </span>
  <a data-text-id="18358460370114327223" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


